Refactor the Protocol Builder architecture so that protocol templates are no longer embedded inside ProtocolBuilder.jsx.

The component has become too large because it mixes:
- UI rendering
- protocol generation logic
- protocol template data
- protocol metadata

The goal is to separate concerns and prepare the system for scalable protocol management.

==================================================
OBJECTIVE
==================================================

Move protocol definitions out of ProtocolBuilder.jsx and prepare the application to load protocol templates from Firebase.

Do not move all business logic into Firebase.
Keep protocol generation and validation logic in code.

==================================================
SECTION 1 — REMOVE EMBEDDED PROTOCOL DATA FROM PROTOCOLBUILDER.JSX
==================================================

Identify all hardcoded protocol templates, protocol variants, protocol names, peptide lists, durations, and descriptive metadata currently embedded inside ProtocolBuilder.jsx.

Remove these protocol data structures from the component.

ProtocolBuilder.jsx should remain focused on:
- step orchestration
- UI rendering
- state coordination
- calling services/repositories

==================================================
SECTION 2 — CREATE A PROTOCOL DATA LAYER
==================================================

Introduce a protocol data layer.

First create a repository abstraction:

protocolRepository

This repository will be responsible for:
- loading approved protocol templates
- filtering by clinical objective
- returning available protocol options
- loading protocol variants / tempos

Do not connect UI directly to Firebase.

==================================================
SECTION 3 — PREPARE FIREBASE COLLECTIONS
==================================================

Create Firebase collections for protocol data.

Required collections:

protocol_templates
monitoring_profiles

Optional future collections:

protocol_variants
validation_profiles
clinical_objectives

==================================================
SECTION 4 — DEFINE PROTOCOL TEMPLATE SCHEMA
==================================================

Each protocol template should support fields such as:

id
name
clinical_objective
summary
peptides
base_duration_weeks
tempo_options
default_tempo
monitoring_profile_id
validation_profile_id
status
visibility
author
tags
priority_weight
version
created_at
updated_at

==================================================
SECTION 5 — KEEP LOGIC IN CODE
==================================================

Do not move the protocol engine fully into Firebase.

Keep in code:

- recommendation logic
- priority ranking
- timeline construction
- confidence scoring
- validation execution
- safety logic

These should live in services such as:

protocolRecommendationService
protocolTimelineBuilder
protocolValidationService
protocolScoringService

==================================================
SECTION 6 — SUPPORT MULTIPLE PROTOCOL OPTIONS
==================================================

The repository and services must support returning:

Top ranked compatible protocol options

not just one protocol.

Each result should include:
- protocol name
- peptides used
- duration
- tempo
- confidence / priority score

==================================================
SECTION 7 — PREPARE FOR VERSIONING AND VISIBILITY
==================================================

Protocol templates in Firebase must support:

status:
draft
reviewed
approved
archived

visibility:
private
organization
public

==================================================
SECTION 8 — DO MIGRATION IN PHASES
==================================================

Phase 1:
Move hardcoded protocols from ProtocolBuilder.jsx into a local data layer.

Phase 2:
Move protocol_templates to Firebase.

Phase 3:
Move monitoring_profiles to Firebase.

Do not attempt a full migration in one step.

==================================================
SECTION 9 — FINAL OBJECTIVE
==================================================

Transform ProtocolBuilder.jsx from a monolithic file into a clean orchestration component backed by:
- repository layer
- protocol services
- Firebase-based protocol content

This should reduce file size, improve maintainability, and support scalable protocol growth.